Join us at our next Courageous Conversation featuring author Jonna Perrillo on Wednesday, May 18 at 6 pm! In "Educating the Enemy: Teaching Nazis and Mexicans in the Cold War Borderlands," Jonna Perrillo explores the assimilation of the children of Nazi scientists into the El Paso public school system while Mexican American children were only permitted at "Mexican schools" and received a highly inequitable education. In this conversation with Jonna Perrillo, we will discuss her research and the question of who is treated justly in American society. Register here: https://us06web.zoom.us/webinar/register/5916523219960/WN_Ul3exOEMSUm8ISH7xTDuiw

Earth Day: How You Can Help Protect Our Community from the Oil Field in Our Backyard At the Pan African Film & Arts Festival we are dedicated to promoting Black stories through the exhibition of film, visual art & other creative expression. For decades, Los Angeles County's oil industry has been given free rein to drill near our communities – including our homes, schools, and hospitals. Now, advocates and residents are using their voices to call out the injustice. Toni Morrison is one of the most celebrated authors in the world with her catalogue of books including, “The Bluest Eye,” “Song of Solomon,” and “Home.” Her work often grappled with issues of race, class, and gender equity, always with a focus on African American culture. She not only dedicated her work to sharing #BlackStories, but her dedication to making space for other Black women and authors to write about our history through the lenses of magical realism and historical fiction was unprecedented. The far-reaching impacts of her work cannot be understated, and her legacy is truly legendary. #BHM2022 #BlackHistoryMonth #BlackHerstoryMonth

Medical racism is real. ⁠ ⁠ This month, we want to celebrate the efforts and achievements of Black menstrual equity activists, while recognizing the disparities that still exist for Black menstruators. ⁠ ⁠ Today’s #TBT is a short clip from PERIOD’s Spotlight Panel on endometriosis which highlights the racial bias and shame that exists in diagnosing this condition. Watch below! https://youtu.be/iV_5XrHdaNM?list=PLztjgSVB9x2NhUsLKmYEVI2rDf_eAy7k7:=:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iV_5XrHdaNM&list=PLztjgSVB9x2NhUsLKmYEVI2rDf_eAy7k7 • • • This panel was moderated by Dr. Rachel Bervell, OB/GYN and Co-Founder of The Black OBGYN Project and included: Dr. Smitha Vilasagar, Minimally Invasive Gynecologic Surgeon, Specializing in Endometriosis Dr. Haben Debessai, Resident Physician Nenji Yilpet, Endometriosis Patient and Advocate, K-12 Educator/Leader Alana Abernethy, Naval Officer, Author, Endometriosis Patient and Advocate Doris Murimi, Founder/CEO of Endo Sisters East Africa Foundation Sandra Eidor, Endometriosis and Infertility Advocate, Founder of Filling Empty Wombs #BlackHistoryMonth #menstrualmovement #endometriosis #period #menstrualequity

Birth control pills are considered to be one of the most important innovations of the 20th century. The ability for women and other people with the capacity for pregnancy to control their reproductive lives is certainly an achievement worth celebrating. However, we also know that family planning tools have been used to subjugate BIPOC women’s reproduction in the past. Join Free the Pill on Friday, February 25 from 12-1:30 pm ET for a webinar bringing together an esteemed panel of Black women for an open discussion about reproductive justice issues surrounding birth control and how, if done right, access to over-the-counter birth control pills can be one critical tool towards equity and bodily autonomy for BIPOC women. Register: bit.ly/FreeThePill-BHM:=:https://us02web.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_PZBlp9urS_OJsZO-tg7_QQ

AntiBlackness is pervasive, ingrained deeply into our society, and is a toxin to our communities. Being ProBlack to us means that we reclaim and restore what is beautiful, powerful, magnetic, and unapologetically US in spite of the fabricated stigmas and myths created about* us. We liberate ourselves as we strive for liberation for our Black community globally. We are creators, innovators, movement leaders, protectors, nurturers, warriors, healers, scholars...every good thing that exists, WE ARE.

March for Moms is celebrating Juneteenth today! Juneteenth commemorates the day in 1865 that the last enslaved African Americans learned they were free. While Confederate soldiers surrendered in April 1865, word didn’t reach the last enslaved Black people in Galveston, Texas until June 19, 1865. While today is a day of celebration, we also reflect on the enduring legacy of slavery and racism that continues, 157 years later, to create worse outcomes for Black birthing people and babies. In 2022, Black women are 3-4 times more likely to die due to childbirth-related causes than white women. Black infants still die at a rate 2-3 times that of white infants. The vast majority of these deaths are preventable. We pause today to celebrate how far we HAVE come, but we recognize how far we still have to go to root out racism in our healthcare systems, public policies, institutions, and culture. We won't rest until Black families have an equal chance to thrive. 🧡

Please join our Center for Healthy Nonprofits on March 8th for their upcoming Ask an Expert Session, "Charting a Course Toward Becoming an Anti-Racist Organization," presented by Anton Russel and Eva Romero. Many organizations have found themselves challenged to explore if “business as usual” is a neutral position in the face of glaring racial inequities across the country. Yet, even when organizations recognize the need to commit to equity work, these questions may remain: Where do we start? What steps can we expect to take? This presentation will use real-life scenarios from our community to discuss what works and what does not. #OnThisDay On This Day, January 21, 1894, Bark Clythia and her cargo of Italian marble wrecked at False Cape. Here is the story, as told by D. Gregory Claiborne Butts in his book "From Saddle To City By Buggy Boat and Railway": Mr. Marchant and I were down there (Cedar Island in Back Bay) on another trip when we had the, to us, unusual experience of being present and lending some assistance to the Life Saving Service at Wash Woods and False Cape in landing a crew of eight Italians, seven Swedes and a negro from the wreck of the Bark "Clythia," on its way from Genoa, Italy to Baltimore, Md., loaded with marble. The crews from the two stations named were on the beach, awaiting the subsidence of the sea, when Marchant and I arrived from the duck blind over in the marsh opposite False Cape. Bill Bowden carried us ashore quickly when both of us expressed the wish to visit the wreck. The captain came ashore first in the Breaches buoy to learn his whereabouts. He said that he thought he was entering Chesapeake Bay off Cape Henry, and was surprised to find himself ashore between two bars cut off from retreat until too late. He went back to the vessel in the buoy, and began sending his men ashore, one at a time; then he himself came. When the negro came he brought with him a large market basket, and in the basket a beautiful brown haired ducking dog, which he gave to John Williams. This splendid animal became the brood dog for scores of ducking dogs throughout that region, and died at last of old age.

"I'm a human being that survived. I helped other people survive." — Stormé DeLarverie Today, I celebrate Stormé DeLarverie, a Black butch lesbian entertainer who played a major role in the Stonewall Uprising, one of the key events that sparked the Gay Liberation and later LGBTQ movement. "It was a rebellion, it was an uprising, it was a civil rights disobedience – it wasn't no damn riot." DeLarverie says of the uprising. She fought back against the police, along with many others, and was brutally beaten. DeLarverie was the only drag king in the Jewel Box Review, the first racially integrated drag revue in the US. Throughout her life, Stormé continued to champion the LGBTQ community, and also regularly performed to raise money for battered women and children. Stormé worked as a nightclub bouncer until age 85 and died in 2014 at the age of 93. . . . [digital collage: faded background, street scene with the Jewel Box Review. Foreground, Stormé DeLarverie, a butch elder, in sunglasses, fedora, and a denim jacket. Quote text "I'm a human being that survived..." overlaid.] #pride

The Orleans Parish School Board unanimously voted to make #AvisWilliams the new superintendent for the NOLA Public Schools’ (NOLA-PS) district. Williams is the first permanent female superintendent in New Orleans in more than 181 years. The news release from OPSB reads as follows: The board and Dr. Williams will now enter contract negotiations. After a successful agreement, she will be formally appointed to the top position during a future board meeting. “This is an historic moment for our school system and for our city, and the board is excited to extend the superintendency to Dr. Avis Williams. As the first African-American woman appointed to lead our district in its more than 180-year history, her breadth of experience as a sergeant in the U.S. Army, a teacher, principal, assistant principal, principal, and superintendent will help take our students’ education to the next level,” said Olin Parker, OPSB president. “Dr. Williams is committed to working with our schools to increase academic achievement, expand access to mental health services for students, and engage deeply with all community members. I am certain of her commitment to ensuring that our graduation rates continue to rise and the doors of success continue to open for our scholars through college, well-paying jobs, and beyond.” Williams is an award-winning, proven instructional leader with experience in innovative practices and strategic planning who has demonstrated an ability to increase student achievement in high poverty schools and improve community support as a teacher, principal, and superintendent of schools. Source: fox8live -- #blackgirlnews

Immigrants make America great, and as elected members in our state legislatures, they provide invaluable representation to the communities they chose to call home. This Immigrant Heritage Month, we want to pay tribute to some of these great Democrats. Wisconsin Rep. Samba Baldeh is an immigrant from Gambia, an IT project manager, and former Madison Common Council president who is the first Muslim ever elected to the state legislature. Virginia Delegate Elizabeth Guzman is an immigrant from Peru who came to the US with only $300. She’s been a champion for unions and workers in the state legislature. Michigan Rep. Padma Kuppami is an experienced engineer in the automotive, finance, and IT industries who was the first Indian immigrant and Hindu elected to the state legislature. Rep. Dan Sena, a former Dreamer who immigrated from Brazil when he was 14, was elected in 2020 to a seat in the Massachusetts House, making him the first Brazillian immigrant ever elected to the legislature. Rep. Gene Wu is a former prosecutor who’s called Texas home since immigrating to the US from China as a child. He proudly represents his Southwest Houston district in the state House, where he is standing up to the GOP’s pro-gun, anti-voting agenda. Rep. Mohamud Noor is a Somali immigrant and state legislator in Minnesota, which is home to the largest Somali diaspora community in the US. In the state House, Mohamud has been a champion for paid family leave. Washington Rep. My-Linh Thai is a Vietnamese refugee and former school board member who has championed legislation for schools, food security, and ensuring the courts are accessible to all, regardless of immigration status. Senator Ghazala Hashmi has been working to foster an inclusive dialogue within her community since she immigrated to the US from India 50 years ago. In 2019, she made history as the first Muslim woman to be elected to the Virginia Senate. Minnesota’s Rep. Fue Lee was born to Laotian parents in a Thai refugee camp before immigrating to the US. In the statehouse, he’s been an environmental justice champion, pushing legislation to protect disadvantaged communities from air pollution. Nevada Assemblywoman Elaine Marzola was born in Brazil and raised in Las Vegas by parents who wanted to give her a better life. She ran for office to be an advocate for education because great schools with excellent teachers make safe communities.

NEW YORKERS DEMAND THAT ICE RELEASE 25-YEAR-OLD TRANS COMMUNITY MEMBER YIMY! #FreeYimy p2a.co/ZSzm8eP This past Christmas, Yimy Aldair Benitez Lopez, a 25-year-old Long Island resident and asylum-seeker from Honduras, was set to complete their gender transition and celebrate their life living fully as a woman. However, on November 7, 2019, Yimy was detained by ICE outside of criminal court and instead spent Christmas in ICE custody in Hudson County Correctional Facility, where they remain to this day. We demand that ICE #FreeYimy immediately. Since they were taken into immigration detention in early November, Yimy has had to stop taking gender-affirming hormones for their own safety, undoing much of the progress they had made towards living as their full self. “The 24th of December was supposed to be the happiest day of my life, the day of the beginning of the new path to live in the world as I am: a transgender woman. It is very difficult for me that this dream was not be realized on this day. But I know that in the future, I will return to this path and I will live in the world as I am.” - Yimy A beloved community member, drag performer, and survivor, Yimy should be released home to Long Island where they can await the result of their appeal before the Board of Immigration Appeals (“BIA”), which will determine whether they can apply for the very first time for asylum, instead of suffering behind bars. Please sign the petition and demand that ICE #FreeYimy immediately! p2a.co/ZSzm8eP

#transgenderawareness. Marsha P. Johnson was one of the key leaders of the Stonewall uprising of 1969, an activist in the Gay Liberation movement and one of the first truth tellers on transgender life. She was also the founder of several organizations: Gay Liberation Front and Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries (S.T.A.R.). Having become homeless on more than one occasion, Johnson was forced to resort to sex work, as she described "in order survive." As a result of this experience, she was a sounding alarm on AIDS and HIV. She brought to light the plight and ostracizing of so many transgender individuals who had to resort to sex work in order to make a living. There is much debate about her actual death, but what is certain is that Marsha was very much harassed by homophobic individuals and her complaints were ignored by police. Despite wanting to make her death a suicide due to past bouts with depression and mental illness, it was later reported that police just did not want to investigate the death of "a black gay" as a homicide. Marsha's fierceness for gay liberation and the acknowledgement of transgender individuals continues to influence the leaders of today. #ccsf #ccsfmovingyouforward #marshpjohnson #gay

I’m fascinated with the connection between the gut and the mind. Our gut is the second brain. It’s lined with trillions of bacteria that digest food. The gut and brain communicate with each other through the vagus nerve. This is why we often see digestive issues in mental health disorders. One study out of Harvard (2018, Molecular Psychiatry) found that “changes in the gut microbiota can control brain insulin signaling and metabolite level which in turn impacts neurobehaviors.” Leaving the gut out of mental health treatment ignores the root cause. Who else geeks out over the gut health?

The pretrial system—an important but often neglected feature of the criminal justice system—affects over 10 million individuals each year who are arrested for an offense in the U.S. The pretrial system operates as one of the earliest points in the criminal justice system and typically represents an individual’s first opportunity to be incarcerated. In theory, the pretrial system is meant to ensure the equitable release of most individuals before trial while minimizing the risk of flight or danger to the public. In reality, however, defendants detained before trial represent over 75% of all jail inmates in some parts of the country, with significantly higher rates of pretrial detention among black and Hispanic individuals. Pretrial detention can also generate substantial spillover effects, as the costs of paying money bail and other related court fees and fines often fall on other family and community members of detained individuals. Many of these harms can result even when the period of incarceration is brief and even if individuals are not ultimately convicted of any crime. The U.S. criminal justice system has experienced a more than threefold expansion in the past several decades. More attention needs to be put into the economic costs of mass incarceration. LEARN MORE: https://fal.cn/3mZTL:=:https://www.cato.org/research-briefs-economic-policy/economic-costs-pretrial-detention Join the conversation using #CatoEcon and follow #CatoCJ for more criminal justice policy analysis.

Today is the anniversary of the #Stonewall Uprising. “A police raid on the Stonewall involving the arrests of 13 people inside the bar met unexpected resistance when a crowd gathered and one of those arrested, a woman, cried out to the assembled bystanders as she was shoved into a paddy wagon, ‘Why don't you guys do something!’” The conflict lasted 6 days. Learn more at https://wea.mobi/3bagRys:=:https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2013/01/an-amazing-1969-account-of-the-stonewall-uprising/272467/ #Pride Image of the stonewall plaque in New York City. The plaque reads “The Stonewall Inn: The events that began at the stonewall inn in 1965 marked a monumental change for lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and queer (LGBTQ) Americans, Stonewall, which occupied 51-53 Christopher Street, was a gay bar that was raided on June 28, 1969. Patrons and a crowd outside resisted, and confrontations continued over the next few nights in nearby Christopher Park and on adjacent streets. This uprising catalyzed the LGBTQ civil rights movement, resulting in increased visibility for the community that continues to resonate in the struggle for equality. New York State Historic Site. 2016”

#VirtualLavenderLabels: Francis Ruyter is a trans man focused on blurring the lines between painting and photography. His signature style consists of flat colors and outlines, applying new media in the vein of Pop Art to images of everyday scenes. Earlier works remain self-reflective of his own experience, while more recent works are inspired by Library of Congress archival images. Through a contemporary lens, he blends classic imagery of Americana with brightly saturated hues. In acrylic on canvas, Walker Evans: Floyd Burroughs and Tengle Children, Hale County, Alabama documents the Great Depression in the United States. Francis references the archives of the U.S. Farm Security Administration to uncover subjects who express the trauma and resilience of the 1920s and 1930s. This work is a dramatic interpretation of a photograph of the same title, published in 1936 by renowned artist and writer, Walker Evans. Additionally, it is part of an extensive series, Let Us Now Praise Famous Men, a collaborative book of Evans' work with text by James Agee. Transcending its original propaganda function, the image contextualizes the American identity in economic and social hardship. It documents the evolution and reconceptualization of Americana through the accessibility of digital archives. How do you believe digital media allows us to distort or reinterpret historical events?

Listen now: audioboom.com/posts/8092517-making-a-difference-lsu-coach-brian-puckett-gives-back-to-hometown:=:https://audioboom.com/posts/8092517-making-a-difference-lsu-coach-brian-puckett-gives-back-to-hometown Often times, various life changes can take us away from where we grew up. For Coach Brian Puckett, his career path has taken him from Rogersville, Alabama, but it will always be his home. One thing I love is when people leave where they consider home, but go back to give back to the place that meant so much to them. On Saturday, Coach Puckett, who is now the head strength and conditioning coach for LSU Basketball, made the over seven hour trip (he had a grand total of 30 hours to spare) from Baton Rouge, Louisiana, to Rogersville to share some of his experiences and knowledge with Lauderdale County High School athletes. I had the opportunity to have not only Coach Puckett on the show, but his mom, Amy, as well to share about his path from Rogersville to Baton Rouge. You can tune in just after 9 p.m. CST/10 p.m. EST tomorrow night (5/30) via FB Podcasts as Coach Puckett and Amy share a powerful message of resilience, strength, focus, and determination. I hope you will make plans to listen! You can also subscribe to TMWS via TuneIn Radio, Apple iTunes, SoundCloud, Audioboom, Spotify, Stitcher, Blubrry, Google Podcasts, & iHeart Radio. This event is FREE to the public! To join, simply register here: https://bit.ly/3tdhSMa.:=:https://mocanyc-org.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZEsceyrrzgjHNO4YifouuC8hpUtt0bE-y0j Please note that this workshop will be recorded via Zoom and available on Facebook Live. What You’ll Need: Paper, 📃 something to draw with (pencils, pens, markers, crayons, whatever you’d like), 🖍 tape, and a cylindrical scroll holder (like a chopstick or extra pen/pencil) About the Comic Artist Laura Gao is the author and illustrator of the Indie Bestseller, “Messy Roots”. Born in Wuhan, China, Gao immigrated with their family to Coppell, Texas where their art career began by doodling on Pokémon cards. Their works have since blossomed to be featured on NPR, the MOCA in NYC, and most notably, their parents’ fridge. After graduating from the University of Pennsylvania, Gao worked in San Francisco as a Product Manager until 2020, when they published a webcomic called “The Wuhan I Know” about their experiences with anti-Asian racism growing up and during COVID. After the comic went viral, they published their debut graphic memoir, “Messy Roots,” and are currently working on a second book. #MuseumFromHome #MuseumAtHome#ProjectsAtHome #ChineseAmerican#Chinatown #DragonBoatFestival #端午节

Pre-order starts today for Songs of Slavery and Emancipation! Listen / pre-order / more info at: jalopyrecords.bandcamp.com/album/songs-of-slavery-and-emancipation:=:https://jalopyrecords.bandcamp.com/album/songs-of-slavery-and-emancipation “These songs of slavery and emancipation, some written more than two hundred years ago, are not only important historically; they have a direct bearing on today’s movements for social and economic transformation. When you hear songs like “Nat Turner” or “Hymn of Freedom,” it’s almost as if they were written yesterday. They bring inspiration and revolutionary clarity to contemporary struggles." - Kali Akuno Executive Director of Cooperation Jackson This double album presents recently discovered songs composed by enslaved people and explicitly calling for resistance to slavery. Some of the songs originate as early as 1800 and others as late as the outbreak of the Civil War. The project also includes long-lost songs of the abolitionist movement, some of which were written by fugitive slaves as well as free black people, challenging common misconceptions of abolitionism. Thirty one songs are presented in a beautiful hardcover bound double CD and digital download containing new performances in a traditional style by numerous contributing artists. An accompanying 64 page liner notes booklet includes complete lyrics as well as reproductions of historic documents. The liner notes also include essays by the album’s producer Mat Callahan, scholar Robin D.G. Kelley and activist organizer Kali Akuno. A companion full length book, to be published by the University Press of Mississippi, documents the sources of these newly released songs, as well as providing historic context: www.upress.state.ms.us/Books/S/Songs-of-Slavery-and-Emancipation:=:https://www.upress.state.ms.us/Books/S/Songs-of-Slavery-and-Emancipation #freedomsongs #abolition #resistancemovement #americanhistory #blm #blacklivesmatter #radicalhistory #shapenote #undergroundrailroad

Since August 2021, over a thousand Afghans have arrived in Georgia, and hundreds more are expected in the upcoming months. Most have been temporarily paroled into the US, and will need immigration legal assistance to remain in the US and seek safety from the Taliban. GAIN is teaming up with International Rescue Committee, Catholic Charities Atlanta, and New American Pathways to serve Afghan parolees in monthly Afghan Pro Se Asylum Clinics. Our first Afghan Asylum Clinic is Saturday, March 26th from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. at New American Pathways: 2300 Henderson Mill Rd Atlanta, GA 30345 We are seeking volunteer attorneys with asylum interest and/or experience to help Afghan parolees prepare their asylum applications, and develop and refine case narratives. Since June 2021, the ADRA in Nepal has been collaborating with hospitals dedicated to combatting COVID-19, as well as rolling out vaccine campaigns in four districts, including Dhanusha, Mahottari, Sarlahi, and Rautahat. “Earlier in the year, ADRA undertook a rapid needs assessment aimed at learning to prioritize the needs of the communities and health facilities,” says Leighton Fletcher, ADRA’s country director in Nepal. “Data collection methods included key informant interviews with selective government representatives, social leaders, and journalists of four districts.” The findings enabled ADRA to respond to the community’s needs more effectively. For Lunar New Year 2022, UNAVSA is excited to announce the first VSAcademy Speaker Series with Professor erin Khuê Ninh, where she will be speaking on the model minority myth, mental health, and imposter syndrome in Vietnamese-American communities. This event will be held virtually on February 2nd, 2022 from 5:00pm to 6:30pm PST. Registration is free and open to members of the VSA space and will feature an interactive workshop, a discussion of Dr. Ninh's book "Passing for Perfect: College Imposters and Other Model Minorities," followed by a Q&A session. Please register for this event by visiting: https://tinyurl.com/unavsaerinninh. Speaker Biography: erin Khuê Ninh is an associate professor in Asian American Studies at the University of California, Santa Barbara. She writes about “model minority subjectivity,” in varying forms. Ingratitude: The Debt-Bound Daughter in Asian American Literature centers on intergenerational conflict in immigrant families. Passing for Perfect: College Impostors and Other Model Minorities asks how it feels to be model minority and how that might drive some to truly desperate lies.

We stand firmly against injustice in all forms and strongly in support of those working to change institutional racism and discrimination. We hear you, we serve you, and we are your Allies.

May is Asian American and Pacific Islander Heritage Month and we're celebrating members of the AAPI community who have made significant contributions to medicine, health care and public health in Texas. Today we're honoring Dr. Kinya Tsukahara (1873-1928). One of the first Japanese immigrants in Texas and a 1906 graduate from the University of Dallas Medical Department (now Baylor University College of Medicine), Dr. Tsukahara opened a family medical practice in what is now southeast Dallas.

"Living in Montgomery puts me in a central location to explore the state, so I do. When I recently left my job with the Alabama State Council on the Arts to pursue my own artistic endeavors, it afforded me time to continue my exploration of Alabama and – in particular – the Black Belt, which had piqued my interest while at the Council. It occurred to me one day that within a hundred-mile radius there are points of interest that are internationally recognized. I started thinking that these places, seen through artists’ eyes, are just as interesting and exotic as we think of European villages as being (just not as old). Also, through the years I noticed that the South, in general, is viewed as intriguing, romantic, and definitely unique. So, come along and I’ll introduce you to some of the people and places that embody these perceptions. They’re all day trips from Montgomery, however, if you really want an in-depth experience, you can make your headquarters in Selma for a couple of nights and position yourself in the center of the action. Selma, the Queen City of the Black Belt, is in the middle of it all. So, let’s go …" To take a detailed journey with former AL State Council on the Arts Community Arts Program Manager Kay Jacoby through Alabama's fascinating Black Belt, click on the Spring issue of the Alabama Municipal Journal and scroll to page 23! Enjoy your trip! https://almonline.org/Assets/Files/Alabama%20Municipal%20Journal/JournalArchive/2022/Spring2022_Web.pdf
